liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli chief military spokesperson Daniel Hagari says the death toll of Israeli soldiers has reached 306 and the number of hostages held in the Gaza strip was 203. "Until now we notified the families of 306 fallen soldiers, and the families of 203 hostages," he said at a daily briefing. "We feel the pain of the families and embrace them in this difficult time. "I want to clarify the number of hostages and concentrate on this issue in which we are putting all efforts, and treating is as a significant manner and as high national priority." The health ministry in Gaza on Thursday said at least 3,785 Palestinians had been killed in Gaza in Israeli strikes since October 7. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told US President Joe Biden on Wednesday more than 1,400 Israelis were killed in the October 7 attacks by Hamas. Rear Admiral Hagari said the area surrounding Gaza is still being screened and that check and searches are still being conducted, while it continues to be considered as a warzone. He also said that any attack by Hezbollah on Israel will be "met with a significant response from our side". Daily military briefings have been carried out since the beginning of the war.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Military spokesman says 306 Israeli soldiers killed, 203 taken hostage

props.alt: Daniel Hagari in uniform in front of two Israeli flags speaks at a microphone

children.content: Read Admiral Daniel Hagari.
(Reuters)
Israeli chief military spokesperson
Daniel Hagari
says the death toll of Israeli soldiers has reached 306 and the number of hostages held in the Gaza strip was 203.
"Until now we notified the families of 306 fallen soldiers, and the families of 203 hostages," he said at a daily briefing.
"We feel the pain of the families and embrace them in this difficult time.
"I want to clarify the number of hostages and concentrate on this issue in which we are putting all efforts, and treating is as a significant manner and as high national priority."
The health ministry in Gaza on Thursday said at least 3,785 Palestinians had been killed in Gaza in Israeli strikes since October 7.
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told US President Joe Biden on Wednesday more than 1,400 Israelis were killed in the October 7 attacks by Hamas.
Rear Admiral Hagari said the area surrounding Gaza is still being screened and that check and searches are still being conducted, while it continues to be considered as a warzone.
He also said that any attack by Hezbollah on Israel will be "met with a significant response from our side".
Daily military briefings have been carried out since the beginning of the war.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The executive committee of the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation (OIC) has released a lengthy communiqué following an emergency meeting of member-state foreign ministers in Saudi Arabia on Wednesday regarding the Israel-Gaza conflict. The communiqué details 20 resolutions from the meeting, condemning what it calls Israel's "blatant and unprecedented aggression" in the occupied territories and the resulting displacement of Palestinians in the Gaza Strip. The OIC calls on member states to "apply all feasible and effective diplomatic, legal and deterrent measures, to stop the occupying power Israel's crimes against humanity". The communiqué also calls on "international actors to engage in sponsoring a serious political path to achieve peace based on ending the illegal Israeli occupation that had begun in 1967 and implementing the two-state solution". But it does not mention Hamas's deadly cross-border terrorist attack launched on southern Israeli communities on October 7. You can read the communique in full here. The OIC is an intergovernmental committee of 57 states including countries such as Indonesia, Saudi Arabia, Pakistan, Iran, Egypt, Jordan and Lebanon.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Islamic countries accuse Israel of 'unprecedented aggression'

props.alt: Saudi Arabia's Foreign Minister Prince Faisal bin Farhan Al Saud chairs the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation meeting in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia.

The communiqué details 20 resolutions from the meeting, condemning what it calls Israel's "blatant and unprecedented aggression" in the occupied territories and the resulting displacement of Palestinians in the Gaza Strip.
The OIC calls on member states to "apply all feasible and effective diplomatic, legal and deterrent measures, to stop the occupying power Israel's crimes against humanity".

The communiqué also calls on "international actors to engage in sponsoring a serious political path to achieve peace based on ending the illegal Israeli occupation that had begun in 1967 and implementing the two-state solution".
But it does not mention Hamas's deadly cross-border terrorist attack launched on southern Israeli communities on October 7.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: British Prime Minister Rishi Sunak has told Israeli President Isaac Herzog that the UK stands in solidarity with Israel. Sunak said it was also important to provide humanitarian aid to the people of Gaza. "We will stand with you in solidarity with your people and your right to defend yourself, to bring security back to your country to your people, to ensure the safe return of the hostages that have been taken," Sunak said in a televised part of the meeting. He also stressed the need to provide aid to Gazans. "Palestinians are victims of what Hamas has done. It's important that we continue to provide humanitarian access," he said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Sunak says UK stands in solidarity with Israel, important to provide humantarian access to Gaza

children.content: British Prime Minister Rishi Sunak.

He also stressed the need to provide aid to Gazans.
"Palestinians are victims of what Hamas has done. It's important that we continue to provide humanitarian access," he said.
